data = [
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 2,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Type IV</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n    <div class=\"alert alert-warning fontsize14 w-100\">\n        <span class=\"fontsize18\">Key Learning Points</span>\n        \n\n        \n\n\n\n        <p>Biliary tree</p>\n\n        <ul>\n                <li>The Bismuth-Corlette classification is used to describe the morphology of cholangiocarcinomas.</li>\n        </ul>\n        \n        \n\n        <div>\n            <label id=\"KLPSuccessMsg\" style=\"display:none\" class=\"text-success fontsize14\">Your preference has been recorded successfully.</label>\n        </div>\n    </div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>The Bismuth-Corlette classification is as follows:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Type I - below confluence of left and right hepatic ducts</li>\n\n<li>Type II - reaching confluence but not involving left or right\nhepatic ducts</li>\n\n<li>Type III - occluding common hepatic duct and either right\n(IIIa) or left (IIIb) hepatic duct</li>\n\n<li>Type IV - multicentric or bilateral intrahepatic segmental\ninvolvement; or involving confluence and both right and left\nhepatic ducts.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>It is commonly used but does not take into account factors such\nas distant metastases or vessel involvement.</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A patient is diagnosed with cholangiocarcinoma. They have a\nstaging CT which states that the tumour involves both the\nconfluence of the right and left hepatic ducts with tumour\ninvolvement in both ducts.</p>\n\n<p>Which type of cholangiocarcinoma is this according to the\nBismuth-Corlette classification?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"360801\" name=\"rdBtnOption+190694\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"360801\"><span>Type II</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"360800\" name=\"rdBtnOption+190694\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"360800\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Type I</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"360804\" name=\"rdBtnOption+190694\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"360804\"><span>Type IV</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"360802\" name=\"rdBtnOption+190694\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"360802\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Type IIIa</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"360803\" name=\"rdBtnOption+190694\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"360803\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Type IIIb</span></div></div>",
        "id": 2
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 3,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Antimitochondrial</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>Primary biliary <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/278\">cirrhosis</a> (PBC) is a slowly progressive\nautoimmune disease of the liver that primarily affects women in\ntheir fifth decade.</p>\n\n<p>It is characterised by portal inflammation and immune-mediated\ndestruction of the intrahepatic bile ducts which results in reduced\nbile secretion and retention of toxic substances. This leads to\nfurther hepatic damage, fibrosis, and cirrhosis.</p>\n\n<p>Serologically, PBC is characterised by antimitochondrial\nantibodies, which are present in 90-95% of patients (often before\nclinical signs develop) and have a specificity of 98%.</p>\n\n<p>These antibodies are specific for the E2 subunit of the pyruvate\ndehydrogenase complex and it is unclear why they affect only the\nliver when all nucleated cells contain mitochondria. Twin and\nfamily studies suggest there is a significant genetic\npredisposition. Treatment is empirical and patients may go on to\nrequire a liver transplant.</p>\n\n<p>Anticardiolipin antibodies are most commonly associated with\n<a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/469\">antiphospholipid syndrome</a> which increases the risk of\nthrombosis.</p>\n\n<p>Anticentromere antibodies are associated with limited systemic\nsclerosis.</p>\n\n<p>Myeloperoxidase is the antigen which p-ANCA (antineutrophil\ncytoplasmic antibodies) targets. It is associated with a number of\nvasculitides but most classically microscopic polyangiitis.</p>\n\n<p>Antinuclear antibodies are associated with 80-90% of cases of\n<a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/103\">systemic lupus erythematosus</a> but are also found with Sj\u00f6gren's\nsyndrome, <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/105\">rheumatoid arthritis</a>, <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/130\">autoimmune hepatitis</a>, systemic\nsclerosis, and polymyositis and dermatomyositis.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Reference:</strong></p>\n\n<ol>\n<li>Hirschfield GM, et al. <a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/19458352\" target=\"_blank\">Primary biliary <span class=\"\" data-bpid=\"278\">cirrhosis</span> associated with HLA,\nIL12A, and IL12RB2 variants</a>. <cite>N Engl J Med.</cite>\n2009;360:2544-55.</li>\n\n<li>Kaplan MM, Gershwin ME. <a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/16177252\" target=\"_blank\">Primary biliary <span class=\"\" data-bpid=\"278\">cirrhosis</span></a>. <cite>N Engl J\nMed.</cite> 2005;353:1261-73.</li>\n</ol></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 38-year-old woman presents with a recent history of pruritus,\nfatigue, and jaundice.</p>\n\n<p>Liver biopsy revealed periportal fibrosis with periportal\ninflammation and prominent enlargement of the portal tracts.</p>\n\n<p>Which one of the following antibodies is most likely to be found\nin the blood?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117654\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80677\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117654\"><span>Anticentromere</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117657\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80677\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117657\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Antinuclear</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117656\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80677\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117656\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Antimyeloperoxidase</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117655\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80677\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117655\"><span>Antimitochondrial</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117653\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80677\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117653\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Anticardiolipin</span></div></div>",
        "id": 3
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 4,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Primary biliary cirrhosis</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n    <div class=\"alert alert-warning fontsize14 w-100\">\n        <span class=\"fontsize18\">Key Learning Points</span>\n        \n\n        \n\n\n\n        <p>Biliary tree, Liver disorders</p>\n\n        <ul>\n                <li>The two main conditions causing pigmentation and chronic liver disease are primary biliary cirrhosis (PBC) and haemochromatosis.</li>\n        </ul>\n        \n        \n\n        <div>\n            <label id=\"KLPSuccessMsg\" style=\"display:none\" class=\"text-success fontsize14\">Your preference has been recorded successfully.</label>\n        </div>\n    </div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>This woman has clinical evidence of chronic liver disease and\nportal hypertension.</p>\n\n<p>The two main conditions causing pigmentation and chronic liver\ndisease are primary biliary <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/278\">cirrhosis</a> (PBC) and\nhaemochromatosis.</p>\n\n<p>PBC is a chronic cholestatic inflammatory liver disease, the\naetiology of which is probably autoimmune. It most commonly affects\nmiddle-aged women.</p>\n\n<p>There is jaundice with skin pigmentation, risk of developing\n<a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/815\">oesophageal varices</a> and fat malabsorption, leading to deficiency of\nthe vitamins A, D, E, K (hence <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/517\">osteomalacia</a> and also bruising).</p>\n\n<p>Serum antimitochondrial antibody is positive in 95-99%\ncases.</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 48-year-old woman complains of pruritus, steatorrhoea, and\nbruising.</p>\n\n<p>On examination she is jaundiced, pigmented with spider naevi and\nhepatosplenomegaly.</p>\n\n<p>Which is the most likely underlying diagnosis?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117293\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80605\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117293\"><span>Autoimmune hepatitis</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117296\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80605\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117296\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Alpha-1 antitrypsin deficiency</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117295\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80605\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117295\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Alcoholic liver disease</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117297\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80605\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117297\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Wilson's disease</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117294\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80605\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117294\"><span>Primary biliary cirrhosis</span></div></div>",
        "id": 4
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 1,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Primary sclerosing cholangitis</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>The features of episodic bloody diarrhoea and the clinical\nfindings point to a diagnosis of <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/43\">ulcerative colitis</a> (UC).</p>\n\n<p>Alkaline phosphatase and gamma gluteryltransferase can often act\nas non-specific markers of inflammation.</p>\n\n<p>The raised bilirubin points to a more cholestatic process. Drugs\noften cause this but it is not common with loperamide.</p>\n\n<p>The combination of UC and cholestasis really should point to\n<a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/847\">primary sclerosing cholangitis</a> (PSC) the antineutrophil cytoplasmic\nantibody (ANCA) helps a little (this is not a specific marker).</p>\n\n<p><a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/873\">Cholelithiasis</a> is a possibility but rare in young men.</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 32-year-old gentleman was seen in the outpatient clinic with a\nsix week history of diarrhoea.</p>\n\n<p>He admitted to opening his bowels up to eight times per day and\nat least twice at night. He described the diarrhoea as bloody and\nalso had an ache in the left iliac fossa.</p>\n\n<p>He recalled several similar episodes over the past ten years\nwhich were self limiting but he had never sought medical\nadvice.</p>\n\n<p>His general practitioner had started Loperamide.</p>\n\n<p>On examination, he looked generally well but had yellow sclera\nwith mild tenderness in the left iliac fossa; sigmoidoscopy\nrevealed an inflamed mucosa.</p>\n\n<table class=\"marginTop table table-bordered\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<th>Haemoglobin</th>\n<td>102 g/L</td>\n<td>(130-180)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>White cells</th>\n<td>9.0 \u00d710<sup>9</sup>/L</td>\n<td>(4-11)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Platelets</th>\n<td>300 \u00d710<sup>9</sup>/L</td>\n<td>(150-400)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>MCV</th>\n<td>90 fL</td>\n<td>(80-96)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Albumin</th>\n<td>35 g/L</td>\n<td>(37-49)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Bilirubin</th>\n<td>80 \u00b5mol/L</td>\n<td>(1-22)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Aspartate transaminase</th>\n<td>50 U/L</td>\n<td>(5-35)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Alkaline phosphatase</th>\n<td>590 U/L</td>\n<td>(45-105)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Gamma gluteryltransferase</th>\n<td>800 U/L</td>\n<td>(&lt;50)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>C reactive protein</th>\n<td>35 mg/L</td>\n<td>&lt;10)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Anti neutrophil cytoplasmic antibody:</th>\n<td>Detected</td>\n<td>-</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n\n<p>Which is the cause of the liver dysfunction?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118080\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80762\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118080\"><span>Drug induced cholestasis</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118082\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80762\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118082\"><span>Primary sclerosing cholangitis</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118078\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80762\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118078\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Autoimmune hepatitis</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118081\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80762\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118081\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Non-specific markers of inflammation</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118079\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80762\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118079\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Cholelithiasis</span></div></div>",
        "id": 5
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 0,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Type 1 Sphincter of Oddi dysfunction</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n    <div class=\"alert alert-warning fontsize14 w-100\">\n        <span class=\"fontsize18\">Key Learning Points</span>\n        \n\n        \n\n\n\n        <p>Biliary tree</p>\n\n        <ul>\n                <li>Sphincter of Oddi dysfunction (SOD) presents with biliary pain and is often a diagnosis of exclusion.</li>\n        </ul>\n        \n        \n\n        <div>\n            <label id=\"KLPSuccessMsg\" style=\"display:none\" class=\"text-success fontsize14\">Your preference has been recorded successfully.</label>\n        </div>\n    </div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>Echinnococcus (Hydatid disease) is characterised by cystic\ncompression of the biliary tree which would be visible on\ncross-sectional imaging.</p>\n\n<p><a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/847\">Primary sclerosing cholangitis</a> (PSC) is characterised by varying\ndegrees of intra and extra-hepatic biliary stricturing.</p>\n\n<p>Type 1 Sphincter of Oddi dysfunction (SOD) is characterised by\nabdominal pain, deranged liver function tests, a dilated biliary\ntree without strictures, and delayed emptying of contrast at ERCP.\nDelayed excretion of contrast is definitive and Sphincter of Oddi\nmanometry need not be carried out with this finding.</p>\n\n<p>Type 2 SOD is pain with only one of the other criteria from the\ntype 1 definition while type 3 is biliary type pain only. Diagnosis\nin type 3 is supported by abnormal manometry although this will\nonly be present in 12-28% of these patients so the diagnosis is\nmost often one of exclusion.</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A patient who has had a cholecystectomy six months previously\nhas ongoing biliary type pain.</p>\n\n<p>Gastroscopy is normal. CT shows dilated tree. Blood tests reveal\nderanged liver function tests. ERCP shows a dilated biliary tree\nwithout strictures and delayed emptying of contrast.</p>\n\n<p>Which of the following is the diagnosis?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"360751\" name=\"rdBtnOption+190684\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"360751\"><span>Type 1 Sphincter of Oddi dysfunction</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"360753\" name=\"rdBtnOption+190684\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"360753\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Type 3 Sphincter of Oddi dysfunction</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"360750\" name=\"rdBtnOption+190684\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"360750\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Primary sclerosing cholangitis (PSC)</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"360752\" name=\"rdBtnOption+190684\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"360752\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Type 2 Sphincter of Oddi dysfunction</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"360749\" name=\"rdBtnOption+190684\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"360749\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Echinnococcus infection</span></div></div>",
        "id": 6
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 4,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Is characteristically associated with palmar xanthomas</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n    <div class=\"alert alert-warning fontsize14 w-100\">\n        <span class=\"fontsize18\">Key Learning Points</span>\n        \n\n        \n\n\n\n        <p>Biliary tree</p>\n\n        <ul>\n                <li>Prolonged cholestasis causes increased cholesterol with raised trigylcerides and reduced HDL.</li>\n        </ul>\n        \n        \n\n        <div>\n            <label id=\"KLPSuccessMsg\" style=\"display:none\" class=\"text-success fontsize14\">Your preference has been recorded successfully.</label>\n        </div>\n    </div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>In prolonged cholestasis features include:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>increased serum cholesterol</li>\n\n<li>a moderate increase in triglyceride</li>\n\n<li>serum that is not lipaemic, and</li>\n\n<li>reduced HDL levels.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Clinical features include:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>palmar xanthomas, and</li>\n\n<li>tuberous xanthomas (particularly on extensor surfaces).</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Tendinous xanthomas are rare.</p>\n\n<p>Dyslipidemia in the form of elevated serum cholesterol and\ntriglyceride levels is common in PBC, does not increase the risk of\ncardiovascular disease, and does not need to be treated with\nlipid-lowering agents unless other concomitant cardiovascular risk\nfactors are present.</p>\n\n<p>Xanthomas usually only occur if cholestasis has persisted for\nmore than three months (sometimes fat deposits may involve bone and\nperipheral nerves).</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>Which of the following is most correct when considering\ndyslipidaemia in a 57-year-old female with two year history of\nprimary biliary cirrhosis?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117520\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80650\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117520\"><span>Is characteristically associated with tendon xanthomas</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117522\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80650\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117522\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">No evidence of a dyslipidaemia would be expected with this short a duration of disease</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117518\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80650\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117518\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">A lipaemic appearance of the serum</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117519\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80650\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117519\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Is treated with clofibrate therapy</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117521\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80650\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117521\"><span>Is characteristically associated with palmar xanthomas</span></div></div>",
        "id": 7
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 1,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Primary sclerosing cholangitis</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n    <div class=\"alert alert-warning fontsize14 w-100\">\n        <span class=\"fontsize18\">Key Learning Points</span>\n        \n\n        \n\n\n\n        <p>Biliary tree</p>\n\n        <ul>\n                <li>The majority of cholangiocarcinomas are sporadic.</li>\n        </ul>\n        \n        \n\n        <div>\n            <label id=\"KLPSuccessMsg\" style=\"display:none\" class=\"text-success fontsize14\">Your preference has been recorded successfully.</label>\n        </div>\n    </div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p><a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/847\">Primary sclerosing cholangitis</a> (PSC) is the most common risk\nfactor for developing cholangiocarcinoma.</p>\n\n<p>The vast majority of cholangiocarcinomas (70%) are sporadic.\nStudies have suggested that all the factors listed above are all\nrisk factors, in addition to:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>diabetes</li>\n\n<li>fatty liver disease, and</li>\n\n<li>inflammatory bowel disease without PSC.</li>\n</ul></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A patient is diagnosed with cholangiocarcinoma.</p>\n\n<p>Which of the following is the commonest predisposing factor to\ndevelopment of cholangiocarcinoma?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"360797\" name=\"rdBtnOption+190693\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"360797\"><span>Obesity</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"360798\" name=\"rdBtnOption+190693\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"360798\"><span>Primary sclerosing cholangitis</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"360799\" name=\"rdBtnOption+190693\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"360799\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Smoking</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"360795\" name=\"rdBtnOption+190693\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"360795\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Alcohol</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"360796\" name=\"rdBtnOption+190693\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"360796\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Chronic hepatitis B</span></div></div>",
        "id": 8
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 0,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Primary biliary cirrhosis (PBC)</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>Pruritus and lethargy are the classical presenting symptoms of\nprimary biliary <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/278\">cirrhosis</a> (PBC). Patients may have associated\nautoimmune conditions such as thyroid disease, Raynaud's and\nAddison's diseases.</p>\n\n<p>Clinical features include:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Stigmata of chronic liver disease</li>\n\n<li>Excoriations due to pruritus, and</li>\n\n<li>Xanthelasma.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Blood results show elevated ALP and GGT with mildly elevated\ntransaminases. A rise in bilirubin is usually a late sign.\nProthrombin time may also be elevated due to impaired synthetic\nfunction or vitamin K malabsorption. IgM will be raised. AMA\nautoantibodies are positive in 95% of cases.</p>\n\n<p>Abdominal ultrasound must be performed in all cases to exclude\nbiliary duct dilatation. The need for liver biopsy is debated as it\nrarely affects the management but it is indicated in cases of\ndiagnostic uncertainty.</p>\n\n<p>PBC increases the risk of <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/369\">hepatocellular carcinoma</a> but often\nfocal liver lesions are seen on ultrasound in cases of HCC.</p>\n\n<p><a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/721\">Cholangiocarcinoma</a> is associated with primary sclerosing\ncholangitis and biliary dilatation would be seen on the ultrasound\nscan.</p>\n\n<p>Up to 80% of gallstones are asymptomatic but patients can\ndevelop biliary colic, cholecystitis and acute pancreatitis.\nUltrasound would demonstrate the gallstones.</p>\n\n<p>Several drugs can cause abnormal liver function tests but the\nhistory is not suggestive of this.</p>\n\n<div>Reference:</div>\n\n<p>Bloom S, Webster G. <cite>Oxford Handbook of Gastroenterology\nand Hepatology.</cite> 2nd ed. Oxford: Oxford University Press;\n2006.</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 50-year-old woman presents with a three month history of\npruritus and lethargy. She is known to have hypothyroidism. She\ndenies regular alcohol intake.</p>\n\n<p>On examination there is evidence of excoriations and\nxanthelasma.</p>\n\n<p>Her blood results are as follows:</p>\n\n<table class=\"marginTop table table-bordered\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<th>ALT</th>\n<td>75 IU/L</td>\n<td>(5-35)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>AST</th>\n<td>84 IU/L</td>\n<td>(1-31)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>ALP</th>\n<td>465 IU/L</td>\n<td>(45-105)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>GGT</th>\n<td>390 IU/L</td>\n<td>(4-35)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Bil</th>\n<td>15 \u00b5mol/L</td>\n<td>(1-22)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>INR</th>\n<td>1.2</td>\n<td>(&lt;1.4)</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n\n<p>Abdominal ultrasound scan is normal with normal liver parenchyma\nand no biliary duct dilatation.</p>\n\n<p>What is the most likely diagnosis?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398000\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199768\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398000\"><span>Primary biliary cirrhosis (PBC)</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"397998\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199768\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"397998\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Gallstones</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"397999\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199768\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"397999\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Hepatocellular carcinoma (HCC)</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"397996\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199768\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"397996\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Cholangiocarcinoma</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"397997\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199768\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"397997\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Drug-induced hepatitis</span></div></div>",
        "id": 9
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 1,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Primary sclerosing cholangitis</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>This man has <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/278\">cirrhosis</a> with portal hypertension, cholestasis,\nand liver synthetic failure.</p>\n\n<p><a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/847\">Primary sclerosing cholangitis</a> (PSC) has a strong association\nwith <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/43\">ulcerative colitis</a> and is the most likely diagnosis.</p>\n\n<p>There is an increased risk of <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/721\">cholangiocarcinoma</a> with PSC and it\nis possible that his deterioration may be due to the development of\ncholangiocarcinoma.</p>\n\n<p>Drug cholestasis would not explain the stigmata of chronic liver\ndisease (spiders, splenomegaly); neither would colonic\ncarcinoma.</p>\n\n<p>Primary biliary <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/278\">cirrhosis</a> is not associated with UC and is\nuncommon in men.</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 40-year-old male with ulcerative colitis (UC) of 10 years\nduration presented feeling unwell. He has complained of right upper\nquadrant pain and has recently noticed he has started to itch. His\nstools are pale coloured. He is on sulfasalazine and has had only\ntwo previous minor relapses.</p>\n\n<p>On examination he has five spider naevi on the upper trunk. On\nhis abdomen he has a 5 cm hepatomegaly and a tipable spleen, but no\nascites.</p>\n\n<p>Investigations show:</p>\n\n<table class=\"table table-bordered\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<th>Platelets</th>\n<td>110 \u00d710<sup>9</sup>/L</td>\n<td>(150-400)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Prothrombin time</th>\n<td>20 secs</td>\n<td>(11.5-15.5)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum bilirubin</th>\n<td>55 \u00b5mol/L</td>\n<td>(1-22)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum aspartate aminotransferase</th>\n<td>101 U/L</td>\n<td>(1-31)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum alanine aminotransferase</th>\n<td>38 U/L</td>\n<td>(5-35)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum alkaline phosphatase</th>\n<td>482 U/L</td>\n<td>(45-105)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Hepatitis B surface antigen</th>\n<td>Negative</td>\n<td>-</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n\n<p>Which is the most likely diagnosis?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117491\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80644\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117491\"><span>Primary biliary cirrhosis</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117492\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80644\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117492\"><span>Primary sclerosing cholangitis</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117490\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80644\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117490\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Drug cholestasis</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117489\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80644\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117489\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Colonic carcinoma</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117488\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80644\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117488\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Cholangiocarcinoma</span></div></div>",
        "id": 10
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 4,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Pancreatitis</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>Pancreatitis is both the most well known and most common\ncomplication of ERCP, estimates of incidence range from 1.3% to\n6.7%. Different patient populations do have different risks of\ndeveloping this complication. Female sex, age less than 60 and a\nlow probability of structural disease (suggested by a normal\nbilirubin, non-dilated ducts or suspected sphincter of Oddi\ndysfunction) all increase the risk.</p>\n\n<p>Cholangitis is a significant risk in those with obstructive\njaundice or CBD stone and occurs in around 1% of cases (estimates\nrange from 0.5% to 5%).</p>\n\n<p>Gastrointestinal haemorrhage is reported in 0.7-2% of cases, the\nneed for biliary sphincterotomy will increase the likelihood of\nbleeding as a complication (1.5% in recent BSG audit data).</p>\n\n<p>Duodenal perforation is surprisingly common with estimates of\nincidence ranging from 0.3% to 1%.</p>\n\n<p>Cardiorespiratory complications, predominantly related to\nsedation, are a mixed group of conditions and are not infrequent\n(0.5-2.3%).</p>\n\n<div>Reference:</div>\n\n<ol>\n<li>Williams EJ, et al. <a href=\"http://gut.bmj.com/content/57/7/1004.long\" target=\"_blank\">Guidelines on the management of common bile duct\nstones (CBDS).</a> <cite>Gut.</cite> 2008;57:1004-1021.</li>\n</ol></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 67-year-old woman is admitted with jaundice and right upper\nquadrant pain.</p>\n\n<p>Abdominal ultrasound scan demonstrates a gallstone in the common\nbile duct with evidence of intrahepatic bile duct dilatation. She\nis due to undergo endoscopic retrograde cholangiopancreatography\n(ERCP) for biliary sphincterotomy and stone extraction.</p>\n\n<p>According to the British Society of Gastroenterology guidelines\non the management of common bile duct stones (2008)<sup>1</sup>,\nwhat is the most common procedure-related complication?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398277\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199824\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398277\"><span>Cholangitis</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398276\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199824\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398276\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Aspiration pneumonia</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398278\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199824\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398278\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Duodenal perforation</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398279\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199824\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398279\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Gastrointestinal haemorrhage</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398280\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199824\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398280\"><span>Pancreatitis</span></div></div>",
        "id": 11
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 2,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Gall bladder carcinoma</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>The diagnosis is gall bladder carcinoma.</p>\n\n<p>There is gross dilatation of the intrahepatic biliary tree with\nnarrowing of the common hepatic duct, and only proximal filling of\nthe cystic duct due to a large mass replacing the gall bladder.</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 60-year-old is admitted with obstructive jaundice.</p>\n\n<p>\n<script type=\"text/javascript\" src=\"/Shared/JavaScript/ddpowerzoomer.js\"></script><script type=\"text/javascript\">jQuery(document).ready(function($) {$(\"img[id^=2044]\").addpowerzoom( { magnifiersize: [150, 150], largeimage: 'https://media.onexamination.com/MediaBrowser/Thumbs/2044.jpg' } );});</script><img id=\"2044.jpg\" src=\"asset/1.png\"></p>\n\n<p>What is the diagnosis?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"347954\" name=\"rdBtnOption+186152\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"347954\"><span>Sclerosing cholangitis</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"347953\" name=\"rdBtnOption+186152\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"347953\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Pancreatic carcinoma</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"347951\" name=\"rdBtnOption+186152\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"347951\"><span>Gall bladder carcinoma</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"347950\" name=\"rdBtnOption+186152\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"347950\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Caroli's disease</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"347952\" name=\"rdBtnOption+186152\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"347952\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Multiple liver metastases</span></div></div>",
        "id": 12
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 3,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Endoscopic retrograde cholangiopancreatography (ERCP) and endoscopic stone extraction</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n    <div class=\"alert alert-warning fontsize14 w-100\">\n        <span class=\"fontsize18\">Key Learning Points</span>\n        \n\n        \n\n\n\n        <p>Biliary tree</p>\n\n        <ul>\n                <li>ERCP is 1st line treatment for cholangitis caused by obstructing CBD stone.</li>\n        </ul>\n        \n        \n\n        <div>\n            <label id=\"KLPSuccessMsg\" style=\"display:none\" class=\"text-success fontsize14\">Your preference has been recorded successfully.</label>\n        </div>\n    </div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>This patient has severe calculus cholangitis and is failing to\nrespond to appropriate antibiotic therapy. In this group of\npatients ERCP is indicated in order to achieve biliary\ndecompression. Therefore in this case, it would be necessary to\nresuscitate the patient till they are more stable and then conduct\nan ERCP.</p>\n\n<p>Simply adjusting the spectrum of antibiotic therapy in this case\nis unlikely to be adequate, especially considering that she has\nalready received broad-spectrum antibiotic cover which will treat\neven resistant organisms.</p>\n\n<p>Percutaneous biliary drainage (PTC) can be considered as an\nalternative where ERCP fails. Open surgery carries a considerable\nexcess mortality in this group when compared to ERCP and should be\navoided.</p>\n\n<p>Extra-corporeal shockwave lithotripsy does not have a role in\nthis setting and is used in the context of non-acute common bile\nduct stones in patients who are not fit for surgery or ERCP.</p>\n\n<p>MRCP is not indicated as the presence of an obstructing CBD\nstone has already been confirmed on USS.</p>\n\n<div>Reference:</div>\n\n<p>Williams E, et al. <a href=\"http://gut.bmj.com/content/57/7/1004.long\" target=\"_blank\">Guidelines on the management of common bile duct\nstones (CBDS).</a> <cite>Gut.</cite> 2008;57:1004-1021.</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 45-year-old woman is admitted with high fever, rigors,\njaundice and severe right upper quadrant abdominal pain.</p>\n\n<p>On examination she is pyrexial with a temperature of 38.9\u00b0C, a\npulse rate of 120 beats per minute and blood pressure of 67/30\nmmHg. She has a previous history of cholecystitis.</p>\n\n<p>Her liver function tests demonstrate:</p>\n\n<table class=\"marginTop table table-bordered\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<th>Bilirubin</th>\n<td>250 \u00b5mol/L</td>\n<td>(1-22)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>ALT</th>\n<td>103 IU/L</td>\n<td>(5-35)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>ALP</th>\n<td>330 IU/L</td>\n<td>(45-105)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum amylase</th>\n<td>170 IU/L</td>\n<td>(60-180)</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n\n<p>She has an abdominal ultrasound scan which demonstrates a\nthick-walled gallbladder with a number of small stones and a common\nbile duct diameter of 13 mm with a 7 mm common bile duct stone.</p>\n\n<p>Despite treatment with gentamicin and piperacillin-tazobactam\nher infective symptoms and inflammatory markers fail to settle and\nshe remains septic. She is commenced on intravenous fluids\nresuscitation.&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>According to the British Society of Gastroenterology guidelines\non the management of common bile duct stones (2008) what is the\nnext most appropriate step in her management?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398286\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199826\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398286\"><span>Adjustment of antibiotic therapy to broaden spectrum of cover</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398288\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199826\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398288\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Extra-corporeal shockwave lithotripsy to achieve stone dissolution</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398290\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199826\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398290\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Surgical stone extraction and cholecystectomy</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398287\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199826\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398287\"><span>Endoscopic retrograde cholangiopancreatography (ERCP) and\nendoscopic stone extraction</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398289\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199826\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398289\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Percutaneous transhepatic cholangiopancreatography and drainage\n(PTC)</span></div></div>",
        "id": 13
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 0,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Type 1</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n    <div class=\"alert alert-warning fontsize14 w-100\">\n        <span class=\"fontsize18\">Key Learning Points</span>\n        \n\n        \n\n\n\n        <p>Biliary tree</p>\n\n        <ul>\n                <li>Choledochal cysts are an uncommon cause of biliary sepsis in adult life and are classified by the Todani system.</li>\n        </ul>\n        \n        \n\n        <div>\n            <label id=\"KLPSuccessMsg\" style=\"display:none\" class=\"text-success fontsize14\">Your preference has been recorded successfully.</label>\n        </div>\n    </div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>Choledochal cysts are usually diagnosed in the neonatal period\nbut a few are delayed until adulthood. The Todani classification is\nused to define these:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Type 1 - a fusiform dilation of the extrahepatic bile duct\n(CHD/CBD)</li>\n\n<li>Type 2 - a diverticulum of the extrahepatic bile ducts</li>\n\n<li>Type 3 - a choledochcele</li>\n\n<li>Type 4a - multiple cystic dilations, intra and extra hepatic\nducts</li>\n\n<li>Type 4b - multiple cystic dilations, only extra-hepatic</li>\n\n<li>Type 5 - Caroli disease (Congenital polycystic dilatation of\nintrahepatic bile ducts)</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Type 1 is the most common and Type 4 the second most common.</p>\n\n<p>Resection and reconstruction is advised to prevent recurrent\ncholangitis, pancreatitis, and malignant change.</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 19-year-old female presents with jaundice and fever. Imaging\nreveals a previously undiagnosed choledochal cyst. This is\ndescribed as a fusiform dilation of the etra-hepatic common hepatic\nduct.</p>\n\n<p>Which type of choledochal cyst does this represent according to\nthe Todani classification?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"360744\" name=\"rdBtnOption+190683\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"360744\"><span>Type 1</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"360746\" name=\"rdBtnOption+190683\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"360746\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Type 3</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"360748\" name=\"rdBtnOption+190683\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"360748\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Type 5</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"360745\" name=\"rdBtnOption+190683\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"360745\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Type 2</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"360747\" name=\"rdBtnOption+190683\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"360747\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Type 4</span></div></div>",
        "id": 14
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 0,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Psychological factors that may impair compliance with immunosuppression</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>Psychological factors that may impair ability to comply with\nimmunosuppressive treatment are a contraindication to liver\ntransplantation.</p>\n\n<p>Ascites refractory to treatment is an indication not a\ncontraindication to liver transplantation.</p>\n\n<p>The remaining options are all diseases which are potentially\ncurable by transplantation in adults.</p>\n\n<div>Reference:</div>\n\n<ol>\n<li>Bloom S, Webster G. <cite>Oxford Handbook of Gastroenterology\nand Hepatology.</cite> 2nd ed. Oxford: Oxford University Press;\n2006.</li>\n\n<li>Travis SPL, et al. <cite>Pocket Consultant\nGastroenterology.</cite> Oxford: Blackwell Publishing; 2005.</li>\n</ol></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 42-year-old woman with primary biliary cirrhosis and\nprogressive liver failure is awaiting a liver transplant.</p>\n\n<p>Which of the following is a contraindication to liver\ntransplantation?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398124\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199793\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398124\"><span>Psychological factors that may impair compliance with\nimmunosuppression</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398121\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199793\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398121\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Autoimmune chronic hepatitis</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398123\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199793\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398123\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Postviral cirrhosis</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398125\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199793\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398125\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Refractory ascites</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398122\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199793\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398122\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Cryptogenic cirrhosis</span></div></div>",
        "id": 15
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 4,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Endoscopic retrograde cholangiopancreatography (ERCP) and endoscopic stone extraction within 72 hours</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>The history, blood tests and ultrasound findings in this case\nindicate gallstone pancreatitis. Although all the data are not\npresent to calculate a full modified Glasgow score those that are\ngiven indicate a score greater than three which is predictive of\nsevere disease. In patients with gallstone pancreatitis when the\ndisease is predicted to be severe ERCP and endoscopic stone\nextraction should be performed within 72 hours of the onset of\npain.</p>\n\n<p>In patients with mild gallstone pancreatitis, in the absence of\ncholangitis, there is no evidence to support ERCP and stone\nextraction in the acute setting; however arrangements must be made\nfor definitive management of common bile duct stones on the same\nadmission or within two weeks of recovery.</p>\n\n<p>In the context of gallstone pancreatitis and common bile duct\nstones conservative management is not appropriate unless\ncomorbitities or the severity of illness preclude endoscopic or\nsurgical intervention.</p>\n\n<p>A PTC would not be indicated in this setting unless there was\ncholangitis and failure of ERCP to decompress the biliary\nsystem.</p>\n\n<p>Glasgow score for Pancreatitis:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>PaO<sub>2</sub> &lt;7.29 kPa</li>\n\n<li>Glucose &gt;10 mmol/L</li>\n\n<li>Age &gt;55 years</li>\n\n<li>WBC &gt;15</li>\n\n<li>Calcium &lt;2.0 mmol/L</li>\n\n<li>Urea &gt;16 mmol/L</li>\n\n<li>LDH &gt;600 IU/L</li>\n\n<li>Albumin &lt;32 g/L</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>The presence of three or more of these criteria within the first\n48 hours is indicative of severe pancreatitis.</p>\n\n<p>If the score \u22653, severe pancreatitis is likely Referral to the\nHDU/ICU is suggested in this case. If the score &lt;3, severe\npancreatitis is unlikely.</p>\n\n<div>Reference:</div>\n\n<p>Williams EJ, Green J, Beckingham I, et al. <a href=\"http://gut.bmj.com/content/57/7/1004.long\" target=\"_blank\">Guidelines on the management of common bile duct\nstones (CBDS).</a> <cite>Gut.</cite> 2008;57:1004-21.</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 58-year-old man is admitted to hospital with severe central\nabdominal pain, of sudden onset, radiating through to the back. He\nhas no previous past medical history.</p>\n\n<p>On examination he is jaundiced, apyrexial, tachycardic with a\npulse rate of 120 and has central and epigastric abdominal\ntenderness.</p>\n\n<p>Blood tests demonstrate:</p>\n\n<table class=\"marginTop table table-bordered\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<th>White cell count</th>\n<td>25.3 \u00d710<sup>9</sup>/L</td>\n<td>(4-11)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Neutrophils</th>\n<td>19.3 \u00d710<sup>9</sup>/L</td>\n<td>(2.0-7.5)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Amylase</th>\n<td>1,200 IU/L</td>\n<td>(60-180)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>ALT</th>\n<td>110 IU/L</td>\n<td>(5-35)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>AST</th>\n<td>65 IU/L</td>\n<td>(1-31)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>ALP</th>\n<td>230 IU/L</td>\n<td>(45-105)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>LDH</th>\n<td>800 IU/L</td>\n<td>(10-250)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Glucose</th>\n<td>12 mmol/L</td>\n<td>(4-7)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Sodium</th>\n<td>151 mmol/L</td>\n<td>(137-144)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Urea</th>\n<td>17 mmol/L</td>\n<td>(2.5-7.5)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Creatinine</th>\n<td>230 \u00b5mol/L</td>\n<td>(60-110)</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n\n<p>An abdominal ultrasound is performed which shows the presence of\na common bile duct stone and a common bile duct diameter of 11 mm\nwith intrahepatic duct dilatation. There are also several stones in\nthe gallbladder.</p>\n\n<p>According to the British Society of Gastroenterology guidelines\non the management of common bile duct stones (2008) what is the\nmost appropriate course of action with regard to managing his\nbiliary disease?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398284\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199825\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398284\"><span>Percutaneous transhepatic cholangiopancreatography and drainage\n(PTC)</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398281\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199825\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398281\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Conservative management only</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398283\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199825\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398283\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Laparoscopic cholecystectomy and intraoperative stone extraction\nwithin two weeks of recovery from acute illness</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398285\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199825\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398285\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Surgical stone extraction</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398282\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199825\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398282\"><span>Endoscopic retrograde cholangiopancreatography (ERCP) and\nendoscopic stone extraction within 72 hours</span></div></div>",
        "id": 16
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 1,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Acute pancreatitis</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>This gentleman has signs consistent with chronic liver disease\nmost likely a result of chronic alcohol consumption.</p>\n\n<p>He presents with abdominal pain and an elevated amylase.\nAlthough it is not extraordinarily high, this may be a function of\nchronic pancreatic damage.</p>\n\n<p>Ascitic fluid analysis demonstrates a low serum albumin ascites\ngradient (SAAG) - that is, &lt;11 g/L. The fluid is inflammatory -\nraised white cell count, with a predominance of neutrophils. This\nis suggestive of pancreatic ascites and the elevated fluid amylase\nhelps confirm this (particularly the characteristic way in which it\nis in excess of the serum value).</p>\n\n<p>The low lactate dehydrogenase (&lt;225 IU/L) helps exclude a\npolymicrobial ascitic fluid infection which has similar findings\n(additionally there is no mention of finding any organisms on the\nGram stain).</p>\n\n<p>Alcoholic hepatitis is not a cause of ascites, it may occur in\nthe context of pre-existing chronic liver disease where ascites is\nalready present.</p>\n\n<p><a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/278\">Cirrhosis</a> and <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/793\">spontaneous bacterial peritonitis</a> are both\ncharacterised by a high SAAG (&gt;11 g/L) and are differentiated\nfrom each other on the basis of white cell count, Gram stain and\nculture results.</p>\n\n<p>The ascites of <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/369\">hepatocellular carcinoma</a> can be variable,\ndepending particularly on the presence or absence of underlying\nliver disease. Usually, particularly where there is also <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/278\">cirrhosis</a>\nof the liver, the ascites associated with <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/369\">hepatocellular carcinoma</a>\nshares the same features as that in spontaneous bacterial\nperitonitis (high SAAG, high neutrophil count) but is culture\nnegative and cytology positive.</p>\n\n<p>The ascites alpha-fetoprotein level may be raised but only if\nthe serum value is also raised.</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 34-year-old male presents to the Emergency department with\nabdominal pain and distension. He admits to significant alcohol\nexcess, drinking at least half a bottle of spirits per day.</p>\n\n<p>On examination he is jaundiced with numerous spider naevi. He is\ntremulous. His abdomen is grossly distended and shifting dullness\nis present, no organomegaly can be palpated.</p>\n\n<p>His blood tests reveal:</p>\n\n<table class=\"marginTop table table-bordered\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<th>Haemoglobin</th>\n<td>113 g/L</td>\n<td>(130 - 180)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>White cell count</th>\n<td>14.7 \u00d710<sup>9</sup>/L</td>\n<td>(4 - 11)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Platelets</th>\n<td>102 \u00d710<sup>9</sup>/L</td>\n<td>(150 - 400)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Bilirubin</th>\n<td>56 \u00b5mol/L</td>\n<td>(1 - 22)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>ALP</th>\n<td>213 IU/L</td>\n<td>(45 - 10)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>ALT</th>\n<td>34 IU/L</td>\n<td>(5 - 35)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>AST</th>\n<td>80 IU/L</td>\n<td>(1 - 31)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Amylase</th>\n<td>220 IU/L</td>\n<td>(60 - 180)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Albumin</th>\n<td>27 gl/L</td>\n<td>(37 - 49)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>C reactive protein</th>\n<td>63 mg/L</td>\n<td>(&lt;10)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>INR</th>\n<td>1.5</td>\n<td>(&lt; 1.4)</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n\n<p>An ascitic tap is performed and 50 mls of clear yellow fluid are\neasily aspirated from the abdominal cavity. Analysis of the fluid\ndemonstrates that:</p>\n\n<table class=\"marginTop table table-bordered\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<th rowspan=\"2\">Fluid white cell count</th>\n<td>670 cells/mm<sup>3</sup></td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<td>65% neutrophils</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Red cell count</th>\n<td>1,684/mm<sup>3</sup></td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Albumin</th>\n<td>18 g/L</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Amylase</th>\n<td>732 IU/L</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Lactate dehydrogenase</th>\n<td>139 IU/L</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n\n<p>What is the most likely cause of his ascites?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398233\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199815\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398233\"><span>Cirrhosis</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398231\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199815\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398231\"><span>Acute pancreatitis</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398234\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199815\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398234\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Hepatocellular carcinoma</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398235\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199815\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398235\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Spontaneous bacterial peritonitis</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398232\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199815\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398232\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Alcoholic hepatitis</span></div></div>",
        "id": 17
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 3,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Magnetic resonance cholangiopancreatography</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>The history is suggestive of a biliary pathology and the liver\nfunction tests demonstrate a mild obstructive jaundice. The\nultrasound finding of a common bile duct dilatation is suggestive\nof an obstructing stone. Whilst ultrasound is a good preliminary\ninvestigation for common bile duct stones it lacks sensitivity.\nMagnetic resonance imaging is highly effective in confirming the\npresence of common bile duct stones, endoscopic ultrasound (EUS) is\na suitable alternative.</p>\n\n<p>There is no evidence that repeating abdominal ultrasound\nscanning increases the pick-up rate for common bile duct\nstones.</p>\n\n<p>Endoscopic retrograde cholangiopancreatography (ERCP), along\nwith intra-operative cholangiography, is considered the gold\nstandard for diagnosis of common bile duct stones.</p>\n\n<p>However it is an invasive procedure associated with significant\nmorbidity, this patient's sex and young age increase her risk\nof complications at ERCP; thus it should ideally be performed as a\ntherapeutic rather than diagnostic procedure.</p>\n\n<p>The ultrasound demonstrates stones in the gallbladder. There is\nno indication for ERCP in order to remove stones from the\ngallbladder (this requires surgery). The indication for ERCP is for\nthe removal of ductal stones (predominantly CBD stones). The\npresence of a CBD calculus should be confirmed prior to subjecting\nthe patient to a potentially dangerous procedure such as an ERCP -\nMRCP would be the most appropriate test to do this.</p>\n\n<p>The data available from historic studies show that computer\ntomography does not perform well when compared to magnetic\nresonance imaging.</p>\n\n<p>Percutaneous transhepatic cholangiography is an interventional\nradiological procedure which is generally reserved for therapeutic\ndecompression of an obstructed biliary system where ERCP is\nunsuccessful or not possible.</p>\n\n<div>Reference:</div>\n\n<ol>\n<li>Williams E, et al. <a href=\"http://www.bsg.org.uk/attachments/127_cbds_08.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Guidelines on the management of common bile duct\nstones (CBDS)</a>. <cite>Gut</cite> 57:1004-1021.</li>\n</ol></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 45-year-old lady presents with jaundice and right upper\nquadrant pain which is colicky in nature. She has never had any\nsimilar episodes previously.</p>\n\n<p>On examination she is obese and jaundiced, she is apyrexial and\nthere is tenderness in the right upper quadrant without rigidity or\nguarding.</p>\n\n<p>Her liver function tests demonstrate the following:</p>\n\n<table class=\"marginTop table table-bordered\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<th>Bilirubin</th>\n<td>50 \u00b5mol/L</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>ALT</th>\n<td>67 IU/L</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>ALP</th>\n<td>230 IU/L</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum amylase</th>\n<td>140 IU/L</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n\n<p>She has an abdominal ultrasound scan which demonstrates a\nthick-walled gallbladder with a number of small stones and a common\nbile duct diameter of 9 mm (&gt;6 mm abnormal).</p>\n\n<p>According to the British Society of Gastroenterology guidelines\non the management of common bile duct stones (2008)<sup>1</sup>\nwhat is the next most appropriate step in her management?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398275\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199823\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398275\"><span>Repeat abdominal ultrasound scan</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398272\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199823\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398272\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Endoscopic retrograde cholangiopancreatography</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398271\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199823\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398271\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Computer tomography cholangiography</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398273\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199823\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398273\"><span>Magnetic resonance cholangiopancreatography</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398274\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199823\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398274\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Percutaneous transhepatic cholangiography</span></div></div>",
        "id": 18
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 0,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Cholangitis</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>In this case, it is easy to assume an alcohol-related\naetiology.</p>\n\n<p>The patient's lifestyle does fit the profile for alcoholic\nhepatitis. However although the liver function tests may be\nvirtually normal in alcoholic hepatitis an AST to ALT ratio of 2:1\n(or greater) is very suggestive and not present here. The degree of\nhyperbilirubinaemia and coagulopathy in alcohlic hepatitis are\nvariable and are used in assessing the severity of the\ncondition.</p>\n\n<p>His low albumin and platelets along with elevated INR point to\nsignificant underlying liver disease.</p>\n\n<p>Acute on <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/67\">chronic pancreatitis</a> can have normal amylase and this\nis an important differential.</p>\n\n<p>However in this question the triad of fever, jaundice, and RUQ\npain points to cholangitis and the blood tests support this.</p>\n\n<p>Without an USS one cannot be sure about <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/1008\">empyema</a> but clinically\nno mass is felt.</p>\n\n<p>Acute cholecytitis may coexist but the obstruction on the bloods\npoints towards common bile duct pathology.</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 60-year-old man known to have consumed alcohol excessively for\nat least thirty years presented to the emergency unit with\nepigastric and right hypochondrial pain.</p>\n\n<p>He was nauseated, and had vomited several times. He described\nfeeling very hot and sweating profusely. He had been consuming\nalcohol up to the time of admission.</p>\n\n<p>In the past history he recalled that a surgeon had previously\nsuggested a gall bladder operation but he was unsure of the details\nas he had self discharged on that occasion.</p>\n\n<p>On examination he was flushed. He was febrile at 38\u00b0C. Blood\npressure 120/70 mmHg and a of pulse of 100 beats per minute. His\nsclera were yellow. He had eight spider naevi on his upper torso.\nHeart sounds were normal and the chest was clear on auscultation.\nHis abdomen was tender in the right upper quadrant but no mass was\npalpable. There was no detectable ascites and rectal examination\nwas unremarkable.</p>\n\n<p>Investigations revealed:</p>\n\n<table class=\"marginTop table table-bordered\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<th>Haemoglobin</th>\n<td>142 g/L</td>\n<td>(130-180)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>MCV</th>\n<td>101 fL</td>\n<td>(80-96)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>White cell count</th>\n<td>17 \u00d710<sup>9</sup>/L</td>\n<td>(4-11)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Platelets</th>\n<td>110 \u00d710<sup>9</sup>/L</td>\n<td>(150-400)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>International normalised ratio</th>\n<td>1.5</td>\n<td>(&lt;1.4)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum sodium</th>\n<td>139 mmol/L</td>\n<td>(137-144)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum potassium</th>\n<td>4.1 mmol/L</td>\n<td>(3.5-4.9)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum urea</th>\n<td>4.7 mmol/L</td>\n<td>(2.5-7.5)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum creatinine</th>\n<td>101 \u00b5mol/L</td>\n<td>(60-110)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum albumin</th>\n<td>30 g/L</td>\n<td>(37-49)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum total bilirubin</th>\n<td>70 \u00b5mol/L</td>\n<td>(1-22)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Seruma alanine transaminase</th>\n<td>65 U/L</td>\n<td>(1-31)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum aspartate transaminase</th>\n<td>70 U/L</td>\n<td>(5-35)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum alkaline phosphatase</th>\n<td>600 U/L</td>\n<td>(45-105)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum C reactive protein</th>\n<td>100 mg/L</td>\n<td>(&lt;10)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum amylase</th>\n<td>100 U/L</td>\n<td>(60-180)</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n\n<p>Which is the likely diagnosis?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118096\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80765\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118096\"><span>Cholangitis</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118095\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80765\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118095\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Alcoholic hepatitis</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118097\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80765\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118097\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Empyema of the gall bladder</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118094\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80765\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118094\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Acute on chronic pancreatitis</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118093\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80765\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118093\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Acute cholecystitis</span></div></div>",
        "id": 19
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 1,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>MRCP</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>The likely underlying diagnosis is primary sclerosing\ncholangitis (PSC).</p>\n\n<p>The diagnosis is made based upon a combination of clinical\nfeatures, cholestatic liver biochemistry, and characterisitic\ncholangiographic appearances.</p>\n\n<p>Abdominal USS would be the initial investigation in this case\nand may show evidence of intra- and extrahepatic bile duct\ndilatation. Ultrasound is normal in up to half of patients with\nPSC.</p>\n\n<p>An MRCP would be the initial diagnostic investigation of choice\nparticularly given a lower complication rate and its ability to\nimage ducts proximal to obstructing strictures.</p>\n\n<p>ERCP would be reserved for cases where there is still diagnostic\nuncertainty (it still remains the gold standard for establishing\nthe diagnosis) or a need for therapeutic intervention.</p>\n\n<p>Liver histology can be variable and show a wide range of\nchanges. Some changes (periductal fibrosis with inflammation)\nresemble other conditions such as primary biliary <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/278\">cirrhosis</a> and\nchronic active hepatitis. Due to this and the patchy nature of the\ndisease histology may not be diagnostic and a purely histological\ndiagnosis may be incorrect.</p>\n\n<p>Antimitchondiral antibodies are associated with primary biliary\n<a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/278\">cirrhosis</a> (PBC) not PSC.</p>\n\n<p>Withdrawal of his medication will be of no benefit as this\npatient has established liver disease due to PSC rather than drug\nrelated cholestasis.</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 40-year-old male with ulcerative colitis of 10 years duration\npresented with feeling unwell. He has complained of right upper\nquadrant pain and has recently noticed that he has started to itch.\nHis stools are pale coloured. He is on sulfasalazine and has had\nonly two previous minor relapses.</p>\n\n<p>On examination he has five spider naevi on the upper trunk. A\nliver edge is palpable 5 cm below the right costal margin. The tip\nof the spleen is also palpable but there are no signs of\nascites.</p>\n\n<p>Investigations:</p>\n\n<table class=\"marginTop table table-bordered\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<th>Platelets</th>\n<td>110 \u00d710<sup>9</sup>/L</td>\n<td>(150-400)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Prothrombin time</th>\n<td>20 secs</td>\n<td>(11.5-15.5)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum bilirubin</th>\n<td>55 mol/L</td>\n<td>(1-22)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum aspartate aminotransferase</th>\n<td>101 U/L</td>\n<td>(1-31)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum alanine aminotransferase</th>\n<td>38 U/L</td>\n<td>(5-35)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum alkaline phosphatase</th>\n<td>482 U/L</td>\n<td>(45-105)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Hepatitis B surface antigen</th>\n<td>Negative</td>\n<td>-</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n\n<p>Which of the following investigations is the most appropriate\ninitial test to establish the diagnosis?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118060\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80758\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118060\"><span>ERCP</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118058\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80758\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118058\"><span>MRCP</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118059\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80758\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118059\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Liver biopsy</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118061\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80758\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118061\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Antimitochondrial antibodies</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118062\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80758\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118062\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Withdrawal of sulfasalazine</span></div></div>",
        "id": 20
    }
